<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Policeman, Suspected Militant Killed in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A policeman and a suspected Muslim
militant have been killed in southern Egypt during a gun battle in
the first such clash this year, the government said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The shoot-out took place early Friday in the village of Dairout
after security forces opened fire at a truck when it refused to
stop and sped through a checkpoint, injuring one occupant,
Interior Ministry security sources told the country's Middle East
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The others in the truck returned fire, killing one policeman
and injuring another, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The police forces "chased the criminals" and besieged them in a
nearby village and shot one of them dead, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources did not say whether there were other people in the
truck or if the injured man was caught.
</P>
<P>
Dairout is some 330 kilometers south of Cairo in Asyut
Governorate, once a hotbed of an armed insurgency by Islamic
militants who were attempting to oust Egypt's secular government
and replace it with a strict Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
gunmen in the truck were believed to belong to Al-Gamaa
Al-Islamiya, or Islamic Group, the country's most violent militant
group.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic rebellion has been largely crushed by the
government through tightened security measures across the country
and Friday's incident was the first since Al-Gamaa declared a
cease-fire in March. More than 1,200 people, mainly policemen and
militants, have been killed in the insurgency since 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
