<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Below 10 PC African Women in Decision-Making </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Pan-African Women Organization
said Saturday that less than 10 percent of women are currently in
senior positions at decision-making institutions in most of the
African countries.
</P>
<P>
Niepu Troare, executive secretary in charge of the
organization's education and training, revealed this here in the
Angolan capital when marking African Women's Day.
</P>
<P>
Even in sub-Sahara African countries, she said, the percentage
is merely a symbolic 13 percent. That's why the organization was
discontented about the state of African women.
</P>
<P>
Take the example of Tunis in north Africa, only 9.5 percent of
the 163 members of parliament are women. In her home country
Guinea, only 11 out of the total 125 MPs are women.
</P>
<P>
As an observer of the Organization of African Unity, the
Pan-African Organization will in the future commit itself to
helping African governments make and implement policies to improve
the social status of African women, said Troare.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, as member of the United Nations Economic and Social
Council, her organization will lobby unremittingly for women's
participation in social development and try to influence the
council on the resolution of certain major issues.
</P>
<P>
She also suggested that all African countries set up special
ministerial institutions on women's affairs and policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
