<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Opens Fatah Meeting to Seek Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
chaired a meeting of the Fatah movement in Cairo Saturday in the
first step toward unifying Palestinian ranks ahead of the final
status talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in years that the meeting of the Fatah
central committee includes three top party officials who are
opposed to Arafat's peace deals with Israel. The Fatah movement,
led by Arafat, is the main faction of the Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO).
</P>
<P>
By meeting them, Arafat apparently wants to get his own house
in order before beginning reconciliation talks with other PLO
factions opposed to the 1993 Oslo agreement that has formed the
basis of Arafat's off-and-on peacemaking with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The three Fatah officials, namely Director of the PLO Political
Department Farouk Qaddoumi, Fatah military leader Mohammed Jihad,
and Mohammed Ghoneim, in charge of the movement's organizations,
are barred by Israel from entering the Palestinian self-rule areas
and have not attended the previous Fatah meetings held in the Gaza
Strip since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Arafat called Saturday's meeting in Cairo to facilitate their
attendance.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before the meeting started, Palestinian
Planning Minister Nabil Shaath termed the meeting "a good occasion
to meet" the members of the Fatah leadership who "have not
selected to go back home."
</P>
<P>
Shaath expressed hope that every Palestinian will return to the
Palestinian land.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is scheduled to meet on Sunday in Cairo with a
representative of the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine, a key hard-line faction of the PLO, based in Damascus,
Syria.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will meet with Nayef Hawatmeh, leader of the Democratic
Front for the Liberation of Palestine, another Damascus-based
faction, again in Cairo, on August 7.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in the Mediterranean port city of Alexandria
earlier in the day and held talks with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak on Israel's proposals for changes in the last October's
Wye River Accord.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian cabinet has already rejected the Israeli
proposals to skip over parts of the accord, including one of two
Israeli troop pullbacks in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Wye accord stipulates three Israeli troop pullbacks from a
total of 13.1 percent of the West Bank, but it was suspended after
only being implemented the first of the three-phase withdrawal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
