<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Saudi Tent Fire Climbs to 44 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of a tent blaze
in eastern Saudi Arabia climbed to 44 on Saturday as two
fatally-wounded women died at a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
Earlier official Saudi statement said that the fire, which
broke out Wednesday in a tent during a wedding ceremony at
Al-Qudaih village in Qatif, killed 42 people and wounded over 130
others, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the number of those still in hospital dropped
to 109 after some discharges and deaths.
</P>
<P>
The bride who has been in intensive care at a local hospital
since Wednesday, will be transferred, along with three others in
critical condition, to a hospital in the capital of Riyadh, it
added.
</P>
<P>
Thirty bodies have already been buried, while 10 more are
still unidentified due to severe burns.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Health Minister Ussama Shabakshi said that King Fahd and
Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz had ordered that everything
possible to be done to treat the injured.
</P>
<P>
The Governor of the Eastern Province and King Fahd's son,
Prince Mohammad Ibn Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz, had offered over half
million U.S. dollars in compensation for the families that lost
relatives in Wednesday's tragedy.
</P>
<P>
The fire was reportedly caused by an air-conditioning unit
that exploded, sending the burning tent crash down on the wedding
party in the Saudi village.
</P>
<P>
People in the Gulf Arab states, including Saudi Arabia,
still retain the tradition of holding wedding parties in
temporarily-erected tents vulnerable to flames. 
</P>
</TEXT>
