<HEADLINE> New Port to Be Constructed in S. Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government Friday
signed an agreement in principle on the construction of Dobela
Port along the Indian Ocean coast in the south.
</P>
<P>
The deal was signed here between the Public Corporation of
Mozambique's Ports and Railways and the Dobela Development
Corporation of Britain, the Mozambique News Agency reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The port is situated in Matutuine county of Maputo Province,
and about 70 kms away from capital Maputo.
</P>
<P>
The project has a total investment of 515 million U.S. dollars,
60 percent of which will come from the British company, while 40
percent come from the Public Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Jose Antunes, head of the Dobela Development Corporation, said
the new port will cut short the transport distance of ore export
from South Africa's Mpumalange mines by 1,000 kms. At present it
takes about 1,500 kms for the products from the mines to be
exported via Maputo Port to the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The Mpumalange mines produce mainly coal, magnetite and
phosphate. Once the products are exported through Dobela Port,
they will bring about an average 130 million dollars in profit to
Mozambique every year.
</P>
<P>
The new port will occupy 20,000 hectares in land. It is part
of the plan of establishing a special economic zone in the area.
The zone boasts of creating about 10,000 jobs in the first ten
years of its existence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
