<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murder of Taxidriver Prompts Fears for IRA Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A leading member of Progressive
Unionist Party warned Saturday that the murder of a Belfast
taxidriver is proof that the IRA ceasefire is starting to unravel.
</P>
<P>
David Ervine, whose party has links with two of the main
loyalist paramilitary groups, the Ulster Volunteer Force and Red
Hand Commando, said loyalists believed the IRA's ceasefire was
beginning to "fray" following the murder of Charles Bennett in
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
"I think we are beginning to see things fraying at the edges.
That certainly is impressing on the minds of loyalism that the
Good Friday Agreement might not be the vehicle that delivers."
Ervine told Radio Ulster on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"And I think the more that sense of pessimism exists, the worse
things are going to get." he said.
</P>
<P>
Charles Bennett, 22, was found lying shot in the head behind a
social club in west Belfast on Friday, with a cloth over his face
and his hands tied behind his back. He had been missing for five
days.
</P>
<P>
Police had been searching for him all week after he was
reported missing last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Both the Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP) and
unionists have blamed republicans for the murder. Police claimed
that the murder bore all the hallmarks of a paramilitary-style
execution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
