<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Capture Opposition's Only Air Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Taliban militia
Saturday captured Bagram, the only air base of the anti-Taliban
forces led by former defense minister Ahmad Shah Masood, reported
Pakistan Television Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
The loss of Bagram, some 50 kilometers north of the capital
Kabul, will probably turn out to be a major blow to the Masood
forces, analysts here observed.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who control nearly 90 percent of Afghanistan,
launched a major offensive Wednesday against the opposition forces
to extend their rule to the rest of the war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has been raging north of Kabul for three days as the
Taliban managed to seize Nejrab, one of the seven entries into the
Panjsher valley, the opposition forces stronghold, and made
progress towards Bagram.
</P>
<P>
The militia had captured some mountains surrounding Bagram
before they launched a successful attack from Bulemadak Saturday
afternoon, according to informed sources. 
</P>
