<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bio-gas Plants Popular in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Bio-gas plants are gaining
popularity in Dhading district, central Nepal, as an alternative
source of energy for such purposes as cooking and lighting,
reported the official RSS news agency Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The farmers are finding the bio-gas plant useful for protecting
 forests and the environment as it is almost smokeless. Housewives
prefer bio-gas because it is easy to use and does not need to
bother much about maintenance.
</P>
<P>
Another benefit from bio-gas is that it ensures regular supply
of compost for manuring farmland, thereby making farmers
self-reliant, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 500,000 bio-gas plants are now installed across
Nepal and are popular with farmers.
</P>
<P>
More plants are to be installed in the Himalayan Kingdom with
loan investment of various enterprises and undertakings, RSS said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is an agricultural country, where farmers account for 80
percent of its population of 22 million. So the development of
bio-gas plants is meaningful both in energy-saving and in
environmental protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
