<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon and Chile have inked a 10-year pact on
protecting and encouraging investment at the Lebanese Finance
Ministery headqaurters.
</P>
<P>
A Finance Ministry release said that the deal will lay a solid
foundation for upgrading bilateral relations in economy and
investment and pay way for future wide-range cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement that can be renewed will also open the door for
the private sector participation in the joint investment projects,
the the Arabic daily Al-Alam Al-Youm reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The British Marshal Aerospace Corporation would
showcase at the Dubai 2000 Aerospace Fair on Novemebr 14-18 at the
Dubai International Airport Fair Ground.
</P>
<P>
The corporation, specialized in aero maintenance, expected a
Middle East progress in the aviation engineering capabilities over
the coming 10 years, the Al-Alam Al-Youm reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mike Mellon, Aerospace Coordination and Commercial Promotion
manager, said the region will continue developing itself as a
major base for aviation industry.
</P>
<P>
He added that his company will pay further attention to the
region through promoting ties with local firms.
</P>
<P>
The British corporation is developing and responsible for
maintenance for planes of many national carriers and individuals
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has planned to build a bridge across the Nile to
ease the traffic on the Aswan High Dam, Transport and
Communications Minister Soliman Metwalli said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The bridge, estimated to cost 83 million Egyptian pounds (24.41
million dollars), is scheduled to be completed in the second half
of 2000, Metwalli said.
</P>
<P>
It will be a suspension bridge to stretch 5.3 kilometers and
have a width of 24 meters with four lanes, Metwalli was quoted by
the country's Middle East News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The bridge will rise 13 meters above the Nile and have a
250-meter-wide navigation opening to permit the passage of ships.
</P>
</TEXT>
