<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Police Free Women Demonstrators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian police have
released all the women who participated Friday in an illegal
demonstration in capital Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Regional Police Commander Alfred Gewe told reporters here
Saturday that the women were set free hours after they were held
during the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration led to an unrest in which many people on the
street were wounded after rioters began to threw stones, bottles
and pieces of iron at the police.
</P>
<P>
To disperse rioters, policemen fired tear gases and used
pistols, dogs and horses.
</P>
<P>
Gewe said the released women confessed before the law enforcers
that fundamentalists told them to wear hijab, or Moslem headgear,
to make the event colorful and enhance the spirits of the
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
The women were seized along with 75 men who took part in the
riot in areas close to the Manyema Mosque in the downtown Kariakoo
area on Friday afternoon, after mid-day prayers.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Tanzanian Minister of Education and Culture Juma
Kapuya tabled a move before the National Assembly or parliament,
demanding the right for Moslem girls to wear hijab in schools and
when attending Friday prayers.
</P>
<P>
Kapuya, himself a Moslem, later withdrew the move amid concerns
of the majority of members of parliament, who claimed that
Tanzania is a secular country in which students in common schools
are supposed to wear school uniforms when attending classes.
</P>
<P>
Kapuya's change of position has caused wide protests from
Moslems and the riot was ensued.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Vice-President Omar Ali Juma urged people to maintain
peace and security in the country and guard against those who use
religious forums to fulfill their ill intentions.
</P>
<P>
Meeting sheiks and imams in Dar es Salaam, Juma said laid-down
procedures should be followed when people wish to present their
grievances to the government. He said Friday's demonstration was
not the best way.
</P>
<P>
"Since Tanzania has been identified with a haven of peace,
people in the country are proud of peace and tranquillity and we
regard this as the only wealth we possess," he said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president expressed his concern over individuals who
are determined to disrupt the country's peace by inciting hatred.
</P>
<P>
He said the recent grievances presented by Moslems to the
government are being dealt with and some of them will be solved
immediately but others will take time.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the sheiks condemned Friday's demonstration
as a hooligan affair. They said Moslems should be engaged in
activities according to the Koran.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Moslem leaders asked the government to
form a coordination body so as to enable Moslems to channel their
grievances smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The Vice-President directed the Dar es Salaam Regional
Commander to determine who were accidentally rounded up in the
Friday demonstration and set the innocent free as soon as
possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
