<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Swift Vote On Patients' Rights Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday urged Congress to pass the Patients' bill of rights to
expand patients' right under managed health care plans before
Congress starts a long August recess.
</P>
<P>
"The American people sent us to Washington to get work done,
and Congress shouldn't go on summer vacation without voting on the
patient's bill of rights," Clinton said in his weekly radio
address.
</P>
<P>
"This bill should be debated and voted on this coming week,
before Congress adjourns for the summer. If that happens, I
believe the bill would pass." Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The call for patient's rights legislation has intensified in
recent years as Americans have become increasingly frustrated
with cost-conscious managed health care plans.
</P>
<P>
The Senate has passed a bill without the support of the Clinton
administration and Democratic lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has threatened to veto the measure because it covers
only a limited segment of the population and gives far fewer
protections of patients' right than Democrats advocate.
</P>
<P>
The most controversial issue has been whether patients should
have the right to sue Health Managed Organization (HMOs), which
Democrats generally support and most Republicans oppose.
</P>
<P>
The House was expected to vote on a similar bill this week, but
action was derailed when some Republican lawmakers announced their
support for the Democratic version.  
</P>
</TEXT>
