<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Calls for Regional Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa
Saturday called for regional economic integration to protect the
collective interests in the process of globalization.
</P>
<P>
Opening the 73rd Zambia agricultural and commercial show here,
Mkapa said his country "attaches great importance to regional
economic integration as a vehicle of our economic liberation. It
is also an important mechanism of protecting our collective
interests in the process of globalization."
</P>
<P>
Regional integration not only creates bigger markets for the
industries but also provides a more attractive economic space for
foreign investment, said Mkapa, who arrived here Friday for a
three-day visit to Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"As we enter the next millennium, the world is undergoing
fundamental changes that have impact, both negatively and
positively, on the economies and development of our two countries,
and the whole of the African continent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa urged African countries to fight against developments
that clearly are going to marginalize them, or make them net
losers in the evolving world trade regime.
</P>
<P>
He called on poor countries to demand collectively for better
terms and level playing field at the Ministerial Meeting of the
World Trade Organization to be held next November in Seattle, the
United States.
</P>
<P>
"But, at best these will be temporary and should serve as
incentives for redress action by us. We must, therefore, seek to
work hard to reduce the negative impact of globalization on our
economies while maximizing the positive aspects by programed
resort to collective self-reliance and regional economic
integration," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Industrial Development Strategy is geared
to reduce dependence on imported manufactured products from
outside the region. It is also aimed at increasing intra-regional
trade from five percent to 12 percent of the total trade by the
year 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president suggested that Tanzania and Zambia should put in
place a legal and administrative framework to facilitate the
promotion of trade and economic ties.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa invited investors and entrepreneurs from Zambia to invest
in Tanzania, particularly in the field of textiles and garments,
mining, tourism, agriculture and agro-industry.
</P>
<P>
He called on developed countries to immediately reduce the debt
poor countries owe them and increase development assistance to the
poor states.
</P>
<P>
"Africa can, and must, rise again. Our hour is at hand," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We have the natural resources. We have much better policies
and new democratic and visionary leadership in the majority of
African countries. We have our earnest and development aspiring
people."
</P>
<P>
"We can, and must aim higher and work harder toward the
realization of a better world, and a better life, for the Africans
of the new century," the Tanzanian president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
