<HEADLINE> Canadian Women's Water Polo Team Celebrate Historic Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A proud Canadian women's
water polo team are still celebrating their Friday's historic 8-6
victory over the United States in the Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
"I couldn't be better, " beamed Team Canada's Ann Dow." This
medal makes me forget about all the hours we put into this game. I
am so happy and proud."
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in the Pan Am history that women's water
polo medals were awarded.
</P>
<P>
"It means women's water polo is up and running," said Marie
Claude Deslieres. "We now own the first Pan Am Games gold medal
for women's water polo."
</P>
<P>
The game was not as close as the score indicated. Canada's
tenacious defence was in full gear, limiting the Americans to
perimeter shots, and when the ball did get through, Canadian
goalkeeper Josee Marsolais was usually there to stymie the attack.
</P>
<P>
"I am very pleased with all our team," said coach Daniel
Berthelette who at the game's end jumped fully clothed into the
pool.
</P>
<P>
"We know the USA is a good team and we completely cut off their
counter attack."
</P>
<P>
USA coach Guy Baker was gracious in defeat.
</P>
<P>
"Canada controlled the game from the beginning," said Baker, "
We buried ourselves early and never recovered."
</P>
<P>
It was a golden moment for the undefeated Team Canada. "This is
a great day," said Sandra Lize. "My mother became a grandmother
for the first time today, and I got a gold medal for my first
nephew."
</P>
<P>
The victory celebration will be short-lived. The team returns
to the pool in Montreal in just three days to get ready for a
tournament in Italy in two weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
