<HEADLINE> Kuwait Accuses Iraq's 1990 Invasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait renewed Sunday its
condemnation of Iraq for its 1990 invasion, holding Baghdad
responsible for the lost Arab solidarity.
</P>
<P>
"Kuwait is holding the Iraqi regime responsible for the
deteriorating condition and depression among Arab peoples since
the (invasion) disaster," said Deputy Prime Minister and Minister
of State for Cabinet Affairs Mohammad Dheifallah Sharar after the
cabinet's weekly session.
</P>
<P>
Sharar, who is also minister of state for national assembly
affairs, made the remarks on the eve of the ninth anniversary of
the Iraqi invasion, which will be observed Monday.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi troops invaded Kuwait on August 2, 1990 and were ejected
by a U.S.-led coalition force after a seven-month occupation of
the small Gulf emirate.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi occupation "violates all Islamic principles and
international conventions," Sharar was quoted by the Kuwait News
Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti minister also called for an immediate release of
the Kuwaitis and third country's nationals allegedly held in Iraqi
jails. Over 600 Kuwaitis were reported being held in Iraqi
prisons. 
</P>
