<HEADLINE> 174 Passengers, Crew Members Rescued in Philippine Ferry Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 174 people were
rescued, but dozens are still missing after a passenger boat
caught fire off Cebu Island in the Central Philippines Saturday,
the Coast Guard said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report by the Coast Guard said that three people
were killed and 162 were missing in the sea disaster.
</P>
<P>
But the latest report from Cebu said that 174 passengers and
crew members have been rescued so far by fishermen, but 64 are
still missing.
</P>
<P>
Fire broke out hours after the ferry M.V. Rosalia II pulled out
of Cebu early Saturday on a trip to Masbate Island. Passengers
abandoned the vessel after seeing smoke out of the engine room.
</P>
<P>
M.V. Rosalia II was carrying 210 passengers and 28 crew when it
left for Masbate.
</P>
<P>
Rescue work is still going on. Ferries are a popular form of
transport in the Philippines, a country of more than 7,000
islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
