<HEADLINE> Blair Resolves to End N.Ireland Drumcree Impasse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
is intensifying his efforts to end the Drumcree marching in
Northern Ireland, the Downing Street confirmed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Blair's chief of staff, Jonathan Powell, will attend talks next
week aimed at ending an impasse over the annual Drumcree parade
that has become a flashpoint for Northern Ireland tensions, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Powell will return to Belfast, the capital city of the northern
province, and have talks with both sides in the dispute over
whether Protestants should be allowed to parade through a Catholic
enclave each July to mark a centuries-old battlefield victory.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister is determined to find an accommodation.
These talks reflect that," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The parade passed off last month with only minor incidents
after authorities blocked off the controversial part of the
marchers' route. But Protestant Orangemen have continued protests
in the area.
</P>
<P>
"We are expecting to renew contacts next week with the parties
involved in Drumcree. Powell will be involved in that," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
But he declined to say exactly who Powell would meet or where
the talks would take place.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that we are renewing contacts is a reflection of the
prime minister's determination to reach accommodation over this
issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Drumcree issue raised tensions at talks last month chaired
by Blair and Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern and aimed at
brokering a deal over guerrilla disarmament in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Although both Blair and Ahern devoted their efforts, they were
still unable to break the deadlock over disarmament, and
Protestant Unionists pulled out of a power-sharing executive with
Catholics aimed at bringing an end to decades of sectarian
conflict in Northern ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
