<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, August 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA -- A ferry fire that occurred Saturday in central
Philippines killed three people, and 162 others are still missing,
a report of the coast guard said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-three passengers and crew of the ferry M.V. Rosalia II
were rescued after the fire broke out aboard the vessel which was
carrying 210 passengers and 28 crew.
</P>
<P>
Fire broke out when the ferry pulled out of Cebu early Saturday
on a trip to Masbate Island. Passengers abandoned the vessel after
seeing smoke out of the engine room.
</P>
<P>
The rescue work is still on. Ferries are a popular form of
transport in the Philippines, a country of more than 7,000 islands.
(Philippines-Ferry Fire)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian troops foiled a major infiltration bid by
Pakistan in Jammu and Kashmir, killing 12 infiltrators and
injuring 13 others Saturday night, an Indian official spokesman
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that 4 militants were arrested as security
forces smashed some militant hideouts to recover arms and
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
The heavily armed militants entered the Indian territory from
Pakistan-controlled Kashmir, taking advantage of poor visibility
and thick fog through Shamaswari range, according to PTI.
</P>
<P>
They took positions in the rocky area and opened fire on Indian
troops around 15:00 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The shoot-out lasted for nearly three hours. (India-Kashmir-
Infiltrators)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- At least 10 people have died and an estimated 11,380
people have been forced to flee flooded homes between the South
Korean capital of Seoul and the border with the Democratic People'
s Republic of Korea (DPRK) in the aftermath of two days of
torrential rains, government disaster officials said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Two people were missing, the officials added. Media reports
here said that rescue workers in dinghies and helicopters strived
to pick up stranded residents from flooded homes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In some parts of South Korea, many roads and railways have been
damaged. Telephone communications and electricity supply have
also been interrupted.
</P>
<P>
By Sunday afternoon, some floodwaters had abated and people
returned home. But competent authorities have warned that more
heavy rains were expected in the coming two or three days.
</P>
<P>
At least 50.6 centimeters of rain were reported between Seoul
and the border with the DPRK. Disaster officials said rainfall on
Saturday and Sunday alone was about half the amount received by
the area in an average year of rainfall. (SKorea-Rains-Death Toll)
</P>
