<HEADLINE> One Congolese Rebel Faction Signs Cease-fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 1 (Xinhua) --The rebel Movement for the
Liberation for Congo (MLC) fighting to topple President Laurent
Kabila of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) signed here
Sunday the cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Pierre Bemba, who gave a signature on the document, was
praised as a "tremendously responsible" leader by Zambian
President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who mediated the cease-fire agreement, said that it is
a right step toward resolving the conflict in DRC.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed on July 10 by all the six warring
countries involved in the 11-month war in the central African
country. But the rebel Congolese Rally for Democracy (CRD) and the
MLC did not sign because of the disagreement within CRD over who
would on behalf of the group.
</P>
<P>
CRD split into two factions in May this year -- one led by
Emile Illunga and the other by Ernest Wamba Dia Wamba.
</P>
<P>
After signing the agreement Bemba told the press that by
signing the agreement his MLC wants to give peace a chance in his
country. "The region needs a real peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
He condemned President Kabila for unfulfilling his promise to
pursue democratization in his country and construct his country.
</P>
<P>
Representative of the Ugandan President, Kahinda Otafiire, who
 attended Sunday's signing ceremony, denied his country's
involvement in the wrangle within CRD.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want anybody to be left out," said Otafiire, adding
that his country's stance is that everybody should sign the
cease-fire agreement if he wants to bring peace in DRC.
</P>
<P>
Uganda backs both the faction led by Wamba and MLC while Rwanda
 backs the one led by Emile Illunga. 
</P>
</TEXT>
