<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Capture Provincial Capital of Parwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Taliban militia
Sunday continued their northward march and captured Charikar,
capital of Parwan province, some 60 kilometers north of Kabul,
Afghan sources told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the fighters of the militia captured Charikar
and pushed further northwards to enter Jabalus Siraj at 3 p.m.
(local time) and were now romping to take control of the whole
Panjsher Valley.
</P>
<P>
The sources did not provide the figure of casualties.
</P>
<P>
The fall of Jabalus Siraj was not immediately confirmed by the
opposition or independent sources.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban in Saturday night offensive had stunned the
opposition by capturing the strategic Bagram air base, the only
air base of the opposition forces led by former defense minister
Ahmad Shah Masood.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the Taliban forces have also captured a
huge arms cache which the opposition forces used in their attacks
on Kabul, saving the city from more rocket attacks.
</P>
<P>
At least 75 rockets launched from the opposition positions have
exploded in or around Kabul in the last three months alone and
claimed more than a dozen lives.
</P>
<P>
The advances of the student militia have confined the
opposition fighters to mountains. The Taliban are now likely to
attempt to capture Panjsher via Gulbahar, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
The Panjsher Valley has always been a stronghold of Masood and
even the former Soviets failed to capture it during the Afghan war
in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Controlling nearly 90 percent of the country, the Taliban last
Wednesday launched a major offensive in a bid to wipe out the
opposition and extend their rule to the northeast provinces held
by the Masood forces with heavy fortifications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
