<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Term Inter-Faction Dialog Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
opened a dialog here on Sunday with a faction opposed to the Oslo
Accord, an effort to unite Palestinian ranks ahead of the final
status talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's meeting with representatives of the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine (PFLP) was the first of its kind since
the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) signed the first peace
accord with Israel in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The talks broke for lunch after three hours. Participants of
the two sides expressed satisfaction with the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the break, Nabil Shaath, the
Palestinian planning minister and a member of Arafat's delegation,
described the session as a success.
</P>
<P>
"Today we have laid the cornerstone for a successful national
dialog," Shaath said.
</P>
<P>
He said Arafat's Fatah party, the only major PLO faction to
support the Oslo accords, and the PFLP have agreed to "extend the
dialog to include other Palestinian groups and make it
comprehensive."
</P>
<P>
Head of the PFLP delegation, Abu Ali Moustafa, who is also the
party's deputy leader, told reporters that "we are now on the
right path," referring to the meeting with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
While reiterating the PFLP's opposition to the 1993 agreement,
Moustafa termed the Oslo accords as "a thing of the past." "We are
in front of a political reality and we are keen to look to the
future," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for the reinvigoration of the PLO regardless of the
differences of the Palestinian factions.
</P>
<P>
The Fatah movement, the most powerful faction in the PLO, hopes
that its renewed links with the PFLP will encourage other
anti-Oslo factions to return to the Palestinian mainstream.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is scheduled to meet Nayef Hawatmeh, leader of the
Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine (DFLP), in Cairo
on August 7.
</P>
<P>
The DFLP and PFLP are two of the eight Damascus-based
Palestinian factions opposed to the Oslo peace accords. 
</P>
</TEXT>
