<DOCNO> XIE19990801.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Britain Attack Civil Communications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Transport and
Communications Minister Ahmed Murtadha Ahmed said Sunday that the
communication stations which were repeatedly attacked by
U.S.-British warplanes are civil stations and not military ones as
the Americans claimed.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed said the civil stations that provide services to Iraqis
were severely damaged and some of the staff were killed or injured
in the strikes, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the repeated air strikes since last December led
to the break of communications between some Iraqi provinces.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday and Friday, U.S. and British warplanes attacked
some civil and service installations in northern and southern
no-fly zones in Iraq, killing 17 civilians and injuring dozens of
others, said INA.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. said its warplanes attacked military targets in the
no-fly zones, not civil installations as Iraqi claimed.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were set up by the U.S.-led western allies
following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from
possible attacks by Iraqi government troops.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. and Britain launched airstrikes against Iraq
last December, their warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi
military and civilian targets, causing severe civilian casualties
and property damage.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Defense Ministry announced Friday that U.S. warplanes
had attacked Iraqi targets 108 times so far this year. 
</P>
