<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Russian FMs Discuss Mideast Peace March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa Sunday consulted over the telephone with his Russian
counterpart Igor Ivanov the latest developments in the Mideast
peace process.
</P>
<P>
During the telephone conversations proposed by Ivanov, the two
ministers reviewed Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Tuesday and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat on Saturday in Egypt's Mediterranean port of
Alexandria on the implementation of the Wye accord, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Israeli former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
signed the Wye accord last October in Washington, under which
Israel should have pulled out its troops from another 13.1 percent
of the West Bank by the end of last January. But Netanyahu
suspended the accord in December only after the finish of the
first of the three-phase withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Barak has proposed to combine the third troops pullout with the
final status talks that should have started by May 1996. Arafat
has rejected the idea and insisted on a quick implementation.
</P>
<P>
The two officials also dealt with Barak's visit to Russia on
Sunday, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa expressed hope that Russia would continue to play an
active role in the Mideast peace process. For his part, Ivanov
confirmed that Russia remained committed to supporting a
constructive dialog with all parties in the region.
</P>
<P>
Russia, along with the U.S., is a sponsor of the Arab-Israeli
peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
