<HEADLINE> Shandong to Use Overseas Funds for Higher Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province is
to set up a dozen institutions of higher learning with overseas
funds over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The deputy governor of the province, Shao Guifang, said that
overseas enterprises and individuals are encouraged to fund these
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors who establish or expand universities and
colleges in the province will enjoy a series of preferential
policies, such as free use of land and low-interest loans, Shao
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Shao, her province has decided to raise the total
number of private universities and colleges to 120 by the year
2005, from the existing 105, as part of its efforts to ease the
shortage of institutions of higher learning.
</P>
<P>
Only one third of some 300,000 high school graduates in
Shandong are able to enter universities each year.
</P>
<P>
The province has taken steps in recent years to step up the
development of higher education, such as by allowing individuals
to invest in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, China is giving top priority to education by
pursuing the policy of reform and opening-up and vigorously
implementing the strategies of revitalizing China through science
and education, Shao noted.  
</P>
