<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Businessman Imprisoned Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- German businessman Helmut Hofer
who had been released on bail following charges of having illegal
relations with an Iranian Muslim woman, was imprisoned again on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Hofer was sent to the Iranian famous Evin prison in Tehran
because of his contacts with "certain suspicious foreign
elements" and possibility of his escape from the country, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Saeed Nobari, an official from the Tehran's justice department
said that the Iranian security forces had reported to the court on
Hofer's relationship with certain suspicious foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Following receiving the report and conducting necessary
investigations, the branch No. 1406 of Tehran public court issued
an arrest warrant for Hofer in order to prevent him from fleeing
the country, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Hofer was arrested in September, 1997, at Tehran international
airport upon his arrival from Germany with an Iranian woman who
was waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
He was sentenced to death by a local court in Tehran in
January, 1998. According to relevant Iranian laws, non-Muslim men
are forbidden to have any sexual relations with Muslim women.
</P>
<P>
Hofer appealed the court ruling by claiming that he has
converted to Islam before meeting the Iranian woman.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Supreme Court in December turned down the sentence
on Hofer early this year and returned the case to local court for
retrial.
</P>
<P>
The German businessman was released on bail from prison in
April, hours after the German special envoy and Chancellery
Minister Bodo Hombach arrived in Iran to discuss Hofer's case and
bilateral relations with Iranian officials.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder last November appointed
Hombach as his special envoy in charge of Hofer's case and Bonn
has repeatedly called on Tehran to set Hofer free.
</P>
<P>
Germany has been the biggest trade partner of Iran, but the
relations between the two countries have been strained since
April, 1997 after a Berlin court accused Iranian leaders of
sponsoring terrorist assassinations against Iranian dissidents in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
The death sentence against the German businessman Hofer
blocked a rapprochement between Tehran and Bonn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
