<HEADLINE> Sudan Denies Possession of Chemical Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Sudan has categorically
denied that its army is in possession of any kinds of chemical and
biological weapons, asserting that the army has no knowledge about
such weapons.
</P>
<P>
General Mohamed Osman Yassin, spokesman of the Sudanese Armed
Forces, said western media's reports on the use of such weapons by
the Sudanese Army are "absolutely false and full of fabrications,"
Sunday's Sudanese daily "Al Rai Al Am" reported.
</P>
<P>
Yassin predicted that circulation of such reports are a prelude
to military action against the Sudan, adding the Sudanese Armed
Forces are alerted to all possibilities.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the huge military concentrations by Uganda
along the Sudanese borders are still in place and that the
Sudanese Armed Forces are carefully observing such movements.
</P>
<P>
Yassin announced that the Sudanese forces promptly interfered
and restored situation to normal in the Unity State which was
the scene of bloody conflicts between the forces of Rayak Mashar,
Chairman of the Coordination Council of the Southern Sudanese
States, and the forces of Faolino Matib, the pro-government
southern opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
Yassin said that the two parties were urged to get together to
reach a final settlement, asserting that the Sudanese Army is in
control of the situation and that petroleum-rich areas are
absolutely secure.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman accused certain organizations operating in relief
activities of providing the Garang-led popular army, the
government's principal opposition faction, with arms, military
equipment. 
</P>
