<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000-Year-Old Tomb Discovered in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A large ancient tomb dating back
to the Warring State Period (475 B.C.- 221 B.C.) was found
recently in the southeast portion of northern China's Shanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
The tomb is 7.3 meters long, 6.8 meters wide and 12 meters deep.
A large quantity of relics were in the tomb, including bronzeware,
ancient weapons, jade articles, musical instruments, pottery,
lacquerware, and other rare artifacts.
</P>
<P>
Local archeologist said a set of nine pieces of bronzeware
indicates that the tomb's occupant must have been of high position
in the ancient State. These nine items are thought to have been
worn specially by royalty in the Warring States Period.
</P>
<P>
Archeologist also said this discovery will provide valuable
material for the study of the three ancient states of Han, Zhao,
and Wei. 
</P>
