<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Meets With Palestinian Faction Representative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
met here on Sunday with a representative of a faction opposed to
the 1993 Oslo peace accord in a bid to unite Palestinian ranks
ahead of the final status talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's meeting with Abu Ali Moustafa, the No. 2 of the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine (PFLP), was the
first since the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) led by
Arafat signed the first peace accord with Israel in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before the meeting, Moustafa, leading a
six-man PFLP delegation, said his team has come with the hope that
a consensus may be reached to realize "even the minimum of the
Palestinian rights."
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that PFLP leader George Habash refuses to meet
with Arafat until the latter admits that the revocation of
the Palestine National Charter is a mistake.
</P>
<P>
In November, the Palestinians formally revoked parts of the
charter that called for the destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
However, he said Habash's demand is "not an obstacle on the
road to dialog. It is not a precondition."
</P>
<P>
Moustafa reiterated PFLP's opposition to the Oslo agreement,
but said the group has now viewed it as "a political reality."
</P>
<P>
Nabil Shaath, Palestinian planning minister and member of the
central committee of the Fatah movement, told reporters that the
Palestinian mainstream welcomes the talks with the PFLP.
</P>
<P>
Shaath said the Palestinians are close to opening the
negotiations for a final peace deal with Israel, a step which he
said needs support of all Palestinian groups.
</P>
<P>
Fatah, also led by Arafat, is PLO's most powerful movement,
which is the only major force in favor of the Palestinian-Israeli
peace deals.
</P>
<P>
Arafat met the PFLP delegation only hours after he chaired a
five-hour meeting of Fatah's central committee that included a
rare attendance by three of the committee's members opposed to the
Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
The three members, namely PLO Foreign Minister in-exile Farouk
Kaddoumi, Fatah military leader Mohammed Jihad, and Mohammed
Ghoneim, in charge of the movement's organization, are barred by
Israel from entering the Palestinian self-rule areas, where the
central committee meetings are normally held.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the Fatah meeting, Faisal Husseini, an aide of
Arafat, said the committee discussed efforts to seek a national
reconciliation with the rest Palestinian groups.
</P>
<P>
Arafat hopes to hold reconciliation talks with other radical
factions. He is scheduled to meet Nayef Hawatmeh, leader of the
Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine (DFLP), in Cairo
on August 7.
</P>
<P>
The DFLP and PFLP are two of the eight Syrian-based Palestinian
factions opposed to the Oslo accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
