<HEADLINE> Fishing Moratorium in South China Sea Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIHAI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A two-month fishing moratorium
imposed in the South China Sea, the first of its kind in that
region, came to an end today.
</P>
<P>
Fishermen held traditional lion and dragon dances in this
coastal city in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region from midnight
yesterday to celebrate the lifting of the ban. Then, some 1,700
fishing boats were launched today. They will return in about one
week.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17,095 fishing boats from Guangdong and Hainan
provinces, as well as Guangxi, were affected by the fishing ban,
designed to protect local fish resources, according to the Bureau
of Fisheries Management and the South China Sea Fishing Port
Administration.
</P>
<P>
During the moratorium, only seven boats were caught defying the
ban, which was much better than expected. A fisherman told Xinhua
that most of his fellows supported the moratorium.
</P>
<P>
"Fish stocks are shrinking, and so we have had to go further
and further out to sea to look for fish," he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 90,000 fishing boats were affected by this year's
moratorium, imposed on the country's Yellow, Bohai, and East and
South China sea areas. The action is expected to help control the
country's marine output at last year's level of 14.96 million tons,
according to Li Jianhua, deputy director of the Bureau of
Fisheries of the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is planning to introduce a fishing quota
system that is used in developed countries to sustain its fish
resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
