<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mali Troop Starts Leaving S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Mali started withdrawing its
troops in the West Africa Peace Keeping Force (ECOMOG) from Sierra
Leone, according to reports reaching here from Freetown Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant-Colonel Chris Olukolade, spokesman for the
Nigerian-led ECOMOG force, said Saturday in Freetown that
500-strong Malian contingent had received order to withdraw from
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A senior presidential aide of Sierra Leone's President Tejan
Kabbah Saturday commented that the Malian withdrawal plan had
taken his government by surprise. "But we still appreciate what
they have done for us. "
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal follows a peace deal signed in Togo on July 7 by
Sierra Leone President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah and rebel leader Foday
Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
Malian troop's pullout was believed to be linked with lack of
funding and the domestic pressure after a recent S. Leone rebel's
attack on Malian troops in the town of Port Loko. ECOMOG sources
said that up to 10 Malian soldiers were killed in the attack and
up to 10 captured.
</P>
<P>
Malian troops arrived in Sierra Leone in February to reinforce
the Nigeria-dominant ECOMOG force after rebels came close to
taking Freetown in January.
</P>
<P>
An ECOMOG commander in Freetown said that a phased withdrawal
of all the ECOMOG force was planned from August 26, but "We have
received no instructions on that from the Economic Community of
West African States (ECOWAS) secretariat."
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS set up ECOMOG to end the civil war in neighboring
Liberia, and in 1997 the troop's mandate was expanded to help
defense Sierra Leone's elected government from the rebels'
assaults.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the 14000-strong ECOMOG troops are Nigerian, with
about 2,000 Guineans and several hundred Ghanaians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
