<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are brief economic
news from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The new King of Morocco Mohamed VI has proclaimed that
his Kingdom will pursue the policies of economic liberalism,
market economy, political pluralism and decentralisation, and will
establish a state based on rights and law, while, devoting greater
 attention to the social dimensions.
</P>
<P>
According to Sunday's Arab daily "Al Hayat", King Mohamed VI,
in his first speech from the throne, on Friday evening said that
he will be personally concerned about the eradication of poverty,
promotion of social solidarity program, improvement of education,
dealing with the problem of unemployment among youths, and caring
for the Moroccan community abroad and helping them overcome
whatever obstacles facing them.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- An economic report has called for reconsideration
of norms and laws that govern trade exchanges between the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states and other Arab states, with the
aim to facilitating the quick movement of commodities, alleviation
of restrictions on transport measures and cost among Arab states
in future.
</P>
<P>
Today's Egyptian daily "Alam Al Yom" reports that geographic
distribution of last year's trade of the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) has revealed that the European Union, USA and Japan have had
the biggest share in trade. At the same time, the report added,
Asian countries particularly China are assuming mounting
importance with regard to trade. As for the share of the Arab
states and the GCC states in the UAE foreign trade over the past
five years, it remained static.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Airways has announced a 25 per cent reduction on
its regular fare flights from Jedda to Cairo and Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
The local "Iqtissadiya" economic newspaper quoted well-informed
sources as saying that the Saudi Airlines reduced prices of its
Jedda-Cairo-Jedda flights to correspond with the reduction of
Egypt Air prices from July 15 to August 15 during the annual
Egyptian tourism and shopping fair.
</P>
<P>
The sources denied that this step was taken following the
shifting of many clients to Egypt Air flights, pointing out that
this amendment was done with the approval of the two official
carriers in Egypt and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
