<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Russian Border Trade Picking Up Steam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Trucks loaded with timber,
chemical raw materials, steel, clothing, fruits and vegetables are
busily running back and forth via Suifenhe, the biggest border
crossing in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the local port-of-entry administration committee
said that the total volume of transported cargo in the first half
of this year was 980,000 tons, an increase of 14.9 percent over
the corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Guangheng, deputy head of the Heilongjiang Border Trade
Bureau, said that the province's trade volume with Russia in the
first six months was 695.4 million U.S. dollars-worth, or a 24.68
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The overall Sino-Russian trade volume in the first five months
of this year topped 2.2 billion U.S. dollars-worth, 0.7 percent up,
of which exports accounted for 430 million U.S. dollars-worth, and
imports were 1.82 billion U.S. dollars-worth, according to the
latest statistics from the General Administration of Customs. Last
year, Russia ranked the eighth- largest among China's top ten
trade partners.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sino-Russian trade volume in 1998 was only 5.48
billion U.S. dollars-worth, or 10.5 percent down, due to the
impact of the Asian financial crisis and the devaluation of the
ruble.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Russian border trade, starting in the mid-1980s,
experienced a rapid growth at first, but later decreased by a
large margin due to financial turbulence in Russia. As a result,
barter trade developed into spot transactions in 1994. Now it has
entered a second phase, featuring rapid development and the
preponderance of paper pulp, timber, chemical raw materials and
non-ferrous metals, accounting for more than 70 percent, among
China's total imports from Russia. At the same time,over 90
percent of China's exports to Russia are textiles, clothing, food,
light industrial products and construction materials.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said that there are now 606 enterprises in
Heilongjiang engaged in border trade, of which the annual trade
volume of 30 exceeds 20 million U.S. dollars-worth.
</P>
<P>
"This positive trend has made the two state governments
confident that Sino-Russian border trade will progress in a
positive way." said Zhang Jinhe, deputy mayor of Suifenhe city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
