<HEADLINE> Defense Pact with US Opposed by Most Nigerians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New Nigerian, a mainly government-dominant newspaper, said one
of its survey shows that most of the participants of the survey
believe that the proposed pact amount to a humiliation of the
Nigerian military and ungraceful endeavor to find favor with the
western powers.
</P>
<P>
The survey covers former governors, retired military, lecturers
and other members of the public, most of whom contend that the
fear of the Nigerian military which gave vent to the proposal was
not justifiable because the military was now ashamed of the
legacy it left behind after several decades of rule and that the
civil populace was no longer in the mood for another military
interregnum.
</P>
<P>
Coonel Madaki, a former governor, told the survey staff of the
paper that a defense pact could mean a short cut to political
tyranny.
</P>
<P>
However, those in support of the proposal said that Nigeria
would benefit from it if the country is to play effective
leadership on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
The proposed pact was submitted by some senators last month and
had been under debating in the county's top legislature. A high
ranking government official said Friday that the current
administration will not consider signing such a pact, according to
the country's newspapers published Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
