<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Enact Laws on Tobacco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will soon
enact laws regulating the manufacture, sale and smoking in public
to reduce health effects of tobacco consumption.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Jackson Kalweo announced here Saturday that the
 Tobacco Country Bill (1999) soon to be tabled in Parliament, is
one of the government's commitment to the global efforts of
tobacco control program such as the "Tobacco Free Initiative".
</P>
<P>
Local media Sunday quoted Kalweo as saying that the bill aims
at regulating the manufacture, sales, labelling, advertising,
promotion of tobacco products and smoking.
</P>
<P>
Other objectives of the bill, the minister said, include
monitoring and regulating the marketing and promotion of tobacco
products, whether directly or through the sponsoring of other
products, services or events.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the bill will also prohibit smoking in public
places such as cinemas, theatres, health institutions, public
transport and specified buildings.
</P>
<P>
Once enacted, the law will assist in the control of tobacco use
in Kenya's liberalized market which has attracted many local and
imported tobacco products, the minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
