<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana's Death Penalty Hanging on Test Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A hearing in Botswana's High
 Court Monday -- to rule on whether two convicted killers will be
executed -- will have a lasting effect on the issue of capital
punishment in Botswana.
</P>
<P>
It will confirm or change forever the treatment and trials of
those charged with capital offences.
</P>
<P>
The men were granted an 11th-hour stay of execution in January,
when a court ruled that execution by hanging constituted cruel
punishment, and that all laws prescribing executions by hanging
are invalid, according to Sunday World newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Judges said a four-year delay in carrying out the sentence of
death passed on the men was itself cruel, unjust and
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
Application for the stay was brought by Ditshwanelo, the
Botswana Center for Human Rights, with Brian Spilg as leading
counsel.
</P>
<P>
The two men have already won an amendment to prison rules to
allow them to hold confidential discussions with their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Attorney-General Phandu Skelemani has conceded that if some of
the allegations are proved, new trials could be ordered.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers argued that the evidence on which Gwara Brown
Motswetla, 28, and Thabologang Phetolo Maauwe, 30, were convicted
in 1995 for killing a farmer, whose ox they had allegedly stolen,
was largely circumstantial. It was alleged they burnt the farmers
body, but no body, only charred bones, were found.
</P>
<P>
The verdicts and sentences were upheld by the Court of Appeal
and appeals for clemency to the President of Botswana were
refused. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
