<HEADLINE> 2 Iraqis Convicted of Attempted Murder of Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Two Iraqi nationals were sentenced
to prison terms by a Jordanian court Saturday for attempting to
murder an Iraqi diplomat in Amman in January 1998, Jordan Times
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Qassem Mohammad, 24, was sentenced to 10 years in jail with
hard labor and his collaborator Jafar Numan, 28, was given a
7.5-year term for attempting to assassinate Iraqi Charge
D`affaires in Jordan Rahim Tahir in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The two men shot at Tahir near his house in Amman with an
unlicensed gun, but missed the target and were arrested two weeks
later.
</P>
<P>
The court said the two culprits were hired by Tahir's
mother-in-law, identified only as Houileh, who paid them 20
million Iraqi dinars (then almost 13,000 U.S. dollars) for the
murder.
</P>
<P>
Houileh, who was being tried in absentia, had claimed that
Tahir had an affair with another woman and was about to marry her.
</P>
<P>
The verdict by the court will be automatically reviewed by a
higher court within 30 days, Jordan Times said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
