<DOCNO> XIE19990801.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Robot Soccer Puts Chinese World Cup Dream in Sight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese men's national soccer
squad has tried six times and failed in as many bids for the World
Cup finals, and the 2002 premier event maybe still a long shot for
them after just four spots were allotted to Asia.
</P>
<P>
But Chinese scientists may help put China on the world soccer
map and the robots soccer will bring the Chinese fans closer to
the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
The Niuniu team, set up by the Shenyang-based Northeastern
University of China, has booked a finals ticket for the 16-team
fourth Robot Soccer World Cup, an annual event to be run from
August 8-4 in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Xu Xinhe, an official with the International Robot Soccer
Confederation executive committee, played down the prospect for
China for the robot soccer has just gained ground in the soccer-
crazy country.
</P>
<P>
"Compared to the United States and South Korea, we still have a
long way to go. We mainly want to enhance our experience as strive
for results as good as possible." said Xu.
</P>
<P>
"And we till want to make it a chance to promote the bid for
the 2001 World Cup by Shenyang." added Xu.
</P>
<P>
Every World Cup team involves three robots about 15 cms in the
diameter-roughly the size of a tea-cup -- playing on a pitch the
size of a table tennis table. An overhead camera monitors the game
and sends signals to the robots telling them how to move.
</P>
<P>
The RoboCup has attracted an increasingly large following since
it started in Nagoya, Japan in 1997 with 40 teams participating.
</P>
<P>
China has thought the robot soccer merely as a toy to develop
children's intelligence until after the Japan RoboCup when China
took it seriously and launched its research, five years behind the
world tide.
</P>
<P>
While Chinese experts painted a rosy picture, saying that China
is able to become a "robot soccer powerhouse" in the future..
</P>
<P>
"We have lagged well behind in hardware research but we still
have an upperhand in the software development. As long as the
hardware improves, China can gain a spot among the robot soccer
favourites." said Hong Bingrong, president of the Chinese Robot
Association (CRA).
</P>
<P>
Hong's prediction was not ungrounded as more than 30
institutions of higher learning in China have tried their hands in
developing soccer-playing robots and the country has worked out
its own hardware system.
</P>
<P>
China pushed the robot soccer drive by setting up the CRA early
in April and planned to stage the first national competition in
October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
