<HEADLINE> Egypt to Invite Private Sector to Build Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to encourage
investment in energy projects, Egypt plans to invite the private
sector to build two power stations, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper
reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is scheduled to open the bid early next year for the
contracts to build the power stations in the Red Sea town of
Safaga and Sharm el-Sheikh in southern Sinai, Minister of
Electricity and Energy Maher Abaza said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The contracts for building the two 650,000-kilowatts-per-hour
power stations will be issued under BOT (build-operate-transfer)
system, Abaza said.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, the investors are allowed to own and operate
a project for a period of time after constructing it. When the
operating period expires, the project should be transferred to the
Egyptian government.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Electricity Authority has done feasibility studies
for the two projects, which will be linked up to the national
unified power grid, the English-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"The Safaga and Sharm el-Sheikh power stations are part of the
ministry's plan to build up to 15 private-run stations at a total
investment of 7.5 billion Egyptian pounds (2.21 billion U.S.
dollars)," Abaza said.
</P>
<P>
The proposed power stations will increase to six the number of
the private sector-run stations in Egypt, according to the
newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
