<HEADLINE> Major Chinese Tourist City Focusing on Marine Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Qingdao City, a major tourist
attraction in east China's Shandong Province, has set the goal of
becoming a center of marine industries.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao Mayor Wang Jiarui said that both domestic and overseas
investors are especially encouraged to help develop marine
resources using new and high technologies.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, Qingdao has listed the raising and
processing of marine aquatic products, island tourism,
shipbuilding, shipping, and production of pharmaceuticals and
chemicals as key development areas.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that his city boasts many advantages for creating a
marine economy.
</P>
<P>
The city is home to 25 marine research institutes, which employ
more than 5,000 professionals, or 40 percent of the country's
total marine research personnel.
</P>
<P>
The Qingdao Port has become the third largest port of the
country, with an annual handling capacity of 100 million tons of
cargo.
</P>
<P>
This year, the city opened the Qingdao Marine Technology Trade
Center, which focuses on the trading of marine development
technologies, exchange of information concerning marine industries,
and technical services.
</P>
<P>
Faced by the problems of a growing population and a shortage of
onshore resources, China has stepped up efforts to develop its sea
areas. Many coastal provinces, such as Shandong, Zhejiang, Fujian
and Guangdong, are working to turn their marine economy into a
major economic growth area in the years to come. 
</P>
</TEXT>
