<HEADLINE> More Bhang Plantations Found in Central Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- More bhang plantations have been
 discovered in Mount Kenya forest in central Kenya as police are
intensifying operations to rid the forest of drug farms.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Provincial police officer Stanley Manyinya Saturday
said in Embu District in Eastern Province, it is believed that
more than 1,500 acres of the forest are under bhang plantations,
the Sunday Nation newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Manyinya, who is leading a combined force of regular police and
forest rangers in an operation to destroy the drug, said the
fresh farms were discovered at Kiamuriuki and Njuri areas in the
province.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the drug had been replanted on the fields which
previously grew crop, saying a man was shot dead last week during
a confrontation between bhang growers and policer officers.
</P>
<P>
He said the growers, mostly armed with bows, arrows and
home-made guns, guard the bhang fields from tree tops where they
attack anybody approaching.
</P>
<P>
Manyinya believed those guarding the fields were not the real
culprits. " We suspect that these are mere labors who are on the
payroll of drug baron out the forest."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that police officers will continue their operation
to eradiated the illegal framing with sniffer dogs to detect drug
traffickers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
