<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Lamb Farmers Take Anger to U.S. Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Australian lamb producers Sunday
took their anger over U.S. import barriers to the U.S. Embassy in
Canberra, beginning a one-month protest against Washington's
decision before the embassy.
</P>
<P>
Around 30 farmers and their families lit barbecues and hoisted
placards in a park opposite the embassy's main gates as Australian
Federal Police and Protective Service officers stood guard.
</P>
<P>
Australian Agriculture Minister Warren Truss threw his support
behind the protest.
</P>
<P>
"This action demonstrates to the world that the United States
is not fair dinkum about fair trade and does not practice what it
preaches," Truss said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"I support the lamb producers' protest and the Australian
government will fight to have this decision overturned within the
World Trade Organization," he said.
</P>
<P>
The protesters were the first contingent of farmers who will
come from all parts of the New South Wales (NSW) state over coming
weeks to protest against the U.S. decision to hold lamb imports at
1998 levels and impose a tariff of 9 percent on current tonnage.
</P>
<P>
NSW Farmers' Association President John Cobb said the
protesters wanted to remind U.S. Ambassador Genta Hawkins Holmes
and President Bill Clinton that the United States had acted in
defiance of its own free trade rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
The protest was mostly peaceful, although a small group of
farmers did attempt to charge the gates of the embassy as a car
exited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
