<HEADLINE> Papua New Guinea Plans Asset Sales to Pay off Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea (PNG) will
privatize state assets in a bid to pay off a massive public debt
of 2.2 billion kina (845 million U.S. dollars), AAP said.
</P>
<P>
PNG's Prime Minister Mekere Morauta was quoted as saying on
Sunday that his government had established a privatization
commission to implement the program.
</P>
<P>
Morauta said the privatization program was part of his
government's strategy to resurrect PNG's struggling economy.
</P>
<P>
"All sale proceeds will be used to retire public domestic debt,
which has reached the skyrocket figure of 2.2 billion kina," he
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative that we repay this debt as quickly as
possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Sale of government assets is virtually the only way we can
achieve this," Morauta added.
</P>
<P>
Morauta did not specify which government assets were earmarked
for sale but they are likely to be in the telecommunications,
electricity, water and transportation sectors, AAP said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
