<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 06:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Tightens Enforcement of Seat Belt Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian police Sunday started to
enforce a seat belt law strictly in order to check the climbing of
traffic accidents in the country.
</P>
<P>
Under the law passed in 1984, drivers and front seat passengers
in all vehicles are required to fasten their seat belts while
traveling on highways and in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Drivers who fail to do so are expected to be fined up to 50
dinars (70 U.S. dollars) or even have their licenses revoked after
the law is strictly enforced, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
Police surveys conducted during the past few months showed
only 3.7 percent of drivers in Jordan were using seat belts while
driving, while other drivers largely neglected the 1984 law.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics by the Traffic Department, 612 people
died and 171,777 others were injured in 43,343 road accidents in
1998 in the kingdom with a 4.77 million population.
</P>
<P>
Studies indicated 60 percent of the death rates and injuries
in car accidents could be reduced if the drivers and front seat
passengers had fastened their seat belts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990801.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras, Agassi to Crash in Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Top-seeded and defending
champion Andre Agassi and Pete Sampras will renew their longtime
rivalry Sunday when the two Americans square off in the finals of
the Mercedes-Benz Cup tennis tournament.
</P>
<P>
Agassi out-hit unseeded and unheralded Andre Ilie of Australia
6-4, 6-2 in a baseline slugfest Saturday night in the second semi-
final after second-seeded Sampras outclassed Aussie qualifier
James Sekulov 6-0, 6-2 in the day match to earn a place in the
record books.
</P>
<P>
With the 55-minute semi-final victory, Sampras jumped past
Australian Patrick Rafter into the number one spot in the ATP Tour
world rankings. On Monday, Sampras will begin his 271st week at
the top, breaking a tie with Ivan Lendl for the all-time record.
</P>
<P>
The match gave Sampras his 16th consecutive match victory, a
stretch in which he lifted his sixth Wimbledon crown. The 12-time
Grand Slam champion, who has finished a record six straight years
at the top, reflected on his latest milestone.
</P>
<P>
Agassi has won 17 of his last 18 matches, including a French
Open title in his latest summer surge. His only loss came at the
hands of Sampras in the Wimbledon final.
</P>
<P>
Agassi took the opening set with a lone service break in the
fifth game and continued the pressure. Ilie committed three double
faults in the fifth game to give Agassi a 3-2 edge. Another break
made it 5-2 before the American served out the 67-minute match.
</P>
<P>
Sampras looked nearly invincible, yielding just 12 points in
the 23-minute opener, and added two more games before Sekulov got
on the board.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old, 236th-ranked Aussie, who had never won an ATP
Tour match, had a career week despite his loss, beating fifth-
seeded Thomas Enqvist of Sweden and 1996 champion Michael Chang of
the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
