<DOCNO> XIE19990801.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Face Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Millions of Kenyans face the
prospect of hunger by the end of this year following a massive
shortfall in the supply of two household staple foods.
</P>
<P>
Seven million bags of maize (90-kilogram bag) and five million
bags of wheat will have to be imported if famine is to be
averted, the Sunday Standard newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Investigations showed that between now and the harvest of the
current season crop, Kenya needs to import some 180,000 tons of
maize.
</P>
<P>
Another 450,000 tons of maize and about the same amount of
wheat will have to be imported next year because experts predict
this season's produce will not meet the country's food needs.
</P>
<P>
Last week Kenyan Agriculture Minister Musalia Mudavadi said the
country faced a shortfall of two million bags of maize between
July and end of October, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The minister blamed bad weather for the deficit, saying the
long rains between March to June were generally poor for the
maize-growing Nyanza Province and Western Kenya where just about
seven million bags were produced.
</P>
<P>
The bad weather in Coast, North Eastern and Eastern provinces
and low-lying areas in Central Province led to a total crop
failure for the second consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the poor rains, production of the two leading
cereals this season below annual average because of crop damage
caused by army worms, mainly in Rift Valley Province in central
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the National Cereals and Produce Board of Kenya said
 Wednesday that its stock of commercial maize had dwindled to
700,000 bags from 2.3 million bags at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
To solve the impending food shortage, the Kenyan government
announced last Thursday to lower duty on imported maize from 32.5
percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Mudavadi asked traders in the country to source their maize
from the member states of the Common Market of Eastern and
Southern Africa where the duty is two percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
