<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USA Recovers to Deliver More Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Untied States
recovered from their shutout defeat in the track and field
yesterday to score a seven-gold day in the 13th Pan Am Games here
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Three of the four cycling gold on offer went into the American
pockets while in the men's and women's modern pentathlon, the
Americans made a sweeping victory.
</P>
<P>
The American sailors contributed the rest.
</P>
<P>
Now the United States, who were denied any gold in the ten
athletics finals yesterday, had a commanding 69 gold medals, with
Cuba less than half of them standing second on 33 gold. The hosts
Canada, who had a modest day which saw them pull in three gold,
all from sailing, placed third with 31 gold medals.
</P>
<P>
Today saw another country got off to the gold medal standings
table as Carla Malatrasi and partner E. Figueroa Suarez won a
catam hobie 16 open sailing title.
</P>
<P>
Velizar Iliev led an American 1-2 finish in the men's
pentathlon, collecting 5,299 points from all five events of
shooting, fencing,swimming, riding and running to become the
champion of the argueably most demanding event.
</P>
<P>
His woman teammate took the historic title of the women's event
as she garnered 4,992 points to triumph in the Pan Am women's
pentathlon competition, which was first contested in the Games
history.
</P>
<P>
The American cycling upstart Erin Veenstra struck another gold
after her yesterday's 3,000m individual pursuit title, winning an
easy game over her Mexican opponent Belen Guerrero to capture the
25km points women's race.
</P>
<P>
In the Olympic sprint men's event, the American trio Christian
Arrue, Johnny Bairos and Martin Nothstein crossed the line with a
blistering 47.129 seconds, leaving their Cuban opponents a distant
second at 47.899.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old Nothstein afterwards came off his third Pan Am
cycling victory, adding a men's keirin gold to his team and
individual sprint titles.
</P>
<P>
In the men's madison cycling final, Argentine Gabriel Curuchet
and partner Juan Curuchet defied the odds to win the race from
their mighty US rivals James Carney and Brian Whitcomb, preventing
an American clean sweep in today's cycling competitions.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the men's volleyball semi-finals, Cuba came from
one set behind to beat Argentina 28-26, 22-25, 16-25, 22-25 to
reach the final, where they will take on Brazil, a 25-16, 27-25,
25-16 winners over Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
