<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davenport, Williams Meets in Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Lindsay Davenport made light
work of Amy Frazier on Saturday to meet Venus Williams in the
final of the 500,000 U.S. dollars Bank of the West Classic tennis
tournament for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
Titleholder Davenport eased past error-ridden Frazier 6-0, 6-4
in less than an hour in Saturday's semi-finals as second-seeded
Williams won seven straight games during her 6-1, 6-4 victory over
Amanda Coetzer.
</P>
<P>
Davenport, who has a 7-1 record against Williams, claimed the
title of the tournament last year before she took the U.S. Open
crown and the No. 1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
Davenport, who has never lost to Frazier in six matches, played
nearly flawless tennis although her serve became inconsistent in
the last few games of the match.
</P>
<P>
Frazier had six double faults in the opening set and made 18
unforced errors in that set, compared to just five winners.
</P>
<P>
The second semi-final was tied 1-1 in the first set when
Williams began slamming winners from all over the court and won
seven straight games.
</P>
<P>
The American led 4-1 in the second set when Coetzer rallied to
win three consecutive games before Williams recovered to break
Coetzer's serve and then served out the match.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990801.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India not to Withdraw Pakistan's MFN Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- India will not withdraw the
Most-Favored Nation (MFN) status to Pakistan in the wake of the
Kargil conflict.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Minister Ramakrishna Hegde said Sunday that India does
not have any proposal to withdraw the MFN status to Pakistan as he
replied to a question on whether India would consider withdrawal
of MFN status due to the Kargil operations.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan is still to reciprocate though India had
given MFN status to it several years ago, adding "We would still
prefer to wait."
</P>
<P>
Asked if India would consider using the security provisions
under World Trade Organization to slap trade sanctions against
Pakistan, Hegde said, "No."
</P>
<P>
Under Article 22 of WTO, a country can impose trade sanctions
against another in the event of aggression or security threat to
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
