<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Heat Wave Reaches 145 in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The heat wave hitting the
Midwest and the East in the United States has led to the deaths of
at least 145 people since July 19, government officials said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 19 states were reported death in the heat wave.
There are 50 deaths in Illinois, followed by Missouri and Ohio
with 39 and 12 deaths respectively.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, temperatures were over 35 degrees centigrade in
most states in the Midwest and the East. The 40-degree centigrade
reading at Raleigh-Durham International Airport in North Carolina
State broke the 1983 mark of seven days over 37.8 degrees
centigrade in a year.
</P>
<P>
Two cities in Oklahoma State, Hobart and Tipton, hit 42.2
degrees centigrade. Greenville-Spartanburg International Airport
in South Carolina hit a record high of 40 degrees centigrade.
</P>
<P>
Philadelphia City peaked at 37.2 degrees centigrade on Saturday,
making it the ninth straight day above 32.2 degrees centigrade.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in New York City, where temperatures had climbed
above 32.2 degrees centigrade for the last eight days, the
thermometer "only" hit 31 degrees centigrade in Central Park
Saturday. So ended the hottest July in New York City history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
