<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Tourist Arrivals to Hit Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's tourist arrivals this
year will hit an all-time high breaching the 420,000-mark with the
strong performance recorded in the first half of the year,
corporate analysts here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
John Keells Stock Brokers said in a sector review that total
tourist arrivals for the first half at 212,766 was up nearly 23
percent from the 173,145 arrivals recorded during the same period
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The growth received momentum with an increase in Asian arrivals
while a large number of West European arrivals too had helped
improve the picture, the report said.
</P>
<P>
John Keells attributed promotional activities by the government
and several leading tour operators to the increase in arrivals.
</P>
<P>
While West European arrivals clocked a growth of 20.4 percent,
Asian arrivals too recorded a robust 33 percent growth, led by
arrival increases from Japan with 55 percent, and India with 34
percent.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka saw a record tourist arrivals of 407,511 in 1994.
Since then the tourist arrivals have been fluctuating due to the
country's long-running ethnic civil war.
</P>
<P>
It recorded a 4.1 percent increase in tourist arrivals to
381,063 last year after a 21 percent rise in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Tourist Board has predicted a 17 percent rise in tourist
arrivals this year to around 446,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990801.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Inflation Dips to 20-year low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- India's inflation rate dropped
to a two-decade low of 1.62 percent for the week ended July 17,
despite a marginal rise in the Wholesale Price Index (WPI), the
Reserve Bank of India said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the annual rate of inflation is mainly on the
account of a higher base last year due to an abnormal increase in
vegetable prices. For example, the index for vegetables during the
current week is 456.0 compared to 732.1 in the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
During the reference week, the rate of inflation fell by 0.23
percentage points to 1.62 percent (Provisional) from 1.85 percent
the week before. In comparison, the inflation rate was higher at
8.22 percent during the corresponding week of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Wholesale Price Index for All commodities
(base:1981-82=100) during the current week rose by 0.1 percent to
357.3 as against 357.0 in the previous week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990801.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 98,000 Arrested in Combing Drive in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi law-enforcing agencies
had detained a total of 98,601 persons and seized 1,752 firearms
with 7,272 bullets and 878 explosives during the last 100 days of
a country-wide combing drive, according to police sources.
</P>
<P>
Of the arrested, 947 were involved in arms cases, 195 in
explosive cases, 955 were listed "terrorists," 51,091 warrantees
and 45,413 others accused, press reports Sunday quoted the police
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Dhaka Metropolitan Police arrested 14,782 persons including
172 listed "terrorists" with 105 firearms during the period while
the Chittagong Metropolitan Police in the southeast arrested 3,208
persons with 82 arms.
</P>
<P>
The Khulna Metropolitan Police in the southwest arrested 1,448
persons with 94 arms while the Rajshahi Metropolitan Police in the
northwest arrested 813 persons with six arms.
</P>
<P>
The combing force of the ranges of Dhaka, Chittagong, Rajshahi
in the northwest and Khulna in the southwest arrested 19,859
persons with 108 arms, 17,732 persons with 165 arms, 16,950 with
85 arms and 14,696, respectively.
</P>
<P>
During the country-wide combing operation, the government has
set up over 150 police camps at sensitive places, and members of
the paramilitary Bangladesh Rifles and Ansars (village and border
militia) are actively participating in the operation which has
gained the support of the people, Home Minister Mohammad Nasim
said in the parliament last month.
</P>
<P>
The government launched the combing operation on April 22
following bomb explosions early this year in two separate places
that killed several political leaders and activists and injured
many others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
