<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Charges U.S. With not Cleaning Contaminated Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Panama Saturday denounced the
U.S. armed forces for not cleaning areas they used for military
purposes before their withdrawal as they should have done in
accordance with the 1977 Torrijos-Carter treaties.
</P>
<P>
The regional U.S. army headquarters formally departed Panama on
July 30, 25 days ahead of the date agreed on, leaving only a few
hundred soldiers until the Panama Canal is reverted at the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry communique published Saturday said that the
U.S. armed forces abandoned the Emperador firing range, the
bombing area of Balboa Oeste and another installation in Rodman in
advance of the dates agreed on, leaving them contaminated.
</P>
<P>
The government reaffirmed its position that the United States
must comply, even after the handover of the Canal on December 31,
1999, with the decontamination process of the areas used for
military purposes, where they have left non-detonated ammunition
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
Under the Torrijos-Carter treaties signed by Panama and the
United States in 1977, the United States ought to take all
possible measures "for the removal of any threat to human life,
health, and security," and hand over those areas free of risks.
</P>
<P>
But the United States has refused to do the job on the excuse
of lack of technologies in this respect.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the transference of the contaminated areas
in advance was a unilateral decision of the United States and
warned that the abandonment of those areas does not exempt the U.S.
government from its responsibility of decontaminating or
compensating Panama for the loss of assets affected by the
contamination produced by the U.S. armed forces activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
