<DOCNO> XIE19990801.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke080102 -Feature: High-tech Wave Sweeping Across Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Two years after a financial storm
hit Southeast Asia, a new wave of high-tech is sweeping across the
region, where the crisis-affected nations vowed to build their own
"Silicon Valleys" to improve their economic competitiveness in the
world.
</P>
<P>
From the Philippines to Malaysia, Singapore and Thailand,
governments are now determined to develop new technologies to
regain their economic strength, which has been weakened by a
two-year old financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Actually, before the crisis took place in mid-1997, countries
like Singapore, Malaysia and the Philippines had implemented
ambitious plans for hi-tech centers to improve their
competitiveness. But the crisis somewhat marred these projects,
and the competitiveness of the Southeast Asian economies were
partially affected.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1999 World Competitiveness Report published
last month, Southeast Asian nations, except Singapore, appear to
be losing ground in the global race for a competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
While Singapore is placed at the top of the list of the world's
most competitive economies for the fourth straight year, others
are down from 1997. Indonesia, for instance, is down 22 places,
Thailand 12 notches, and Malaysia seven places.
</P>
<P>
To avert the adverse effects of the crisis, Southeast Asian
countries, taking the advantage of an economic turnaround in
recent months, have speeded up the construction of high-tech
centers.
</P>
<P>
Among the ambitious plans, Malaysia's Multi-media Super
Corridor (MSC), a 15km-by-50km hub for pioneering high-tech
research and development in south of Kuala Lumpur, is the most
remarkable one.
</P>
<P>
"I will admit that it is an ambitious project, but it is not
for us Malaysians to implement alone," said Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad. "We conceived it as a giant test-bed
for everyone to use, every one from everywhere."
</P>
<P>
Microsoft, the most prestigious technology company in the
world, is among the 228 foreign and domestic companies that have
got approval to operate in the MSC, and by 2003, 400 high-tech
companies will operate in the "Silicon Valley."
</P>
<P>
Without the MSC, Malaysia, which tries to transform itself into
a knowledge-based economy in the next century, will remain a
manufacturing-based economy fast becoming too expensive to compete
with less developed neighbors, economists said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Philippines does not like to lag behind its
neighbors. As the second largest producer of computer software
exports in Asia next to India, the Philippines is taking its
competitive advantage in quality price and cheaper labor force to
develop information technology.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Software Association estimates that software
services exports will reach 200 million U.S. dollars by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
A visit to Gateway Business Park, 90 minutes by car south of
Manila, could also find a quite high-tech revolution is under way
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Gateway is becoming a center of assembly and testing of some of
the world's most sophisticated computer chips. California-based
Intel is inside with a 550-million-dollar Pentium assembly and a
testing center. Cypress Semiconductor of San Jose and
Massachusetts-based Analog Devices, both with 200-million-dollar
plants, are also inside the park.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, the government is also planning its "Silicon
Valley." It has allocated 176 hectares of land in the west part of
the island to build a high-tech center.
</P>
<P>
As for Thailand, it is stimulating high-tech development by
improving its education system first.
</P>
<P>
According to Sippanondha Ketudat, former education minister of
Thailand, more than 60 percent of the country's workforce has only
primary education, the same level in South Korea 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Thailand trails well behind the region's stronger economies in
providing engineers and scientists, he said, adding "Malaysia has
three to four times as many researchers as Thailand."
</P>
<P>
Realizing the seriousness of the problem, the Thai government
hopes to have steered through the parliament a bill touted as the
most far-reaching education shake-up in a century by early August.
The bill guarantees access to free education for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
By developing high-tech centers, Southeast Asian countries
could make headway in improving their economic competitiveness if
their dreams could become a reality, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
