<BODY>
<HEADLINE> De Bruijn Breaks European Swimming Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Holland's Inge de Bruijn kept her
record-breaking momentum at the European Swimming Championships
here as she set a European record of 24.84 seconds in her 50-meter
freestyle semi-final on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
De Bruijn lowered the mark of 24.88 set by herself last month
and broke a record for the fifth time at the 24th championships.
</P>
<P>
She is yet to challenge in the Sunday's final the world mark of
24.51 set by Le Jingyi of China on September 11, 1994.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, De Bruijn set a championship record in the
same event. She has also broken the European records in the 100-
meter freestyle and butterfly and swam a championship record in a
50-meter butterfly heat earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Dutchman Pieter Van Den Hoogenband saw his bid for a record
seven gold medals was dampened at the Euro event as the
Netherlands was disqualified in the 800 relay final.
</P>
<P>
On the anchor leg, Hoogenband finished nearly three body
lengths ahead of his nearest competitor. But officials ruled that
leadoff swimmer Martyn Zuidweg false started by moving on the
blocks.
</P>
<P>
Italy, who finished second, was also disqualified because
Andrea Beccari, swimming the second leg, left early.
</P>
<P>
Germany, which finished third, was awarded the race in 7:19.63,
followed by Britain in 7:19.91 and Russia in 7:25.36.
</P>
<P>
Hoogenband, who can still tie the six-gold medal record set by
Germany's Michael Gross at the 1985 Euros, entered the 50-meter
freestyle final after going one-two with Russian Alexander Popov,
who holds both the world and European records.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's Lars Frolander won the 100-meter butterfly in 52.61,
followed by Britain's James Hickman in 52.97 and Ukraine's Denis
Sylantyev third in 53.04, just beating Franck Esposito of France,
who won the 200.
</P>
<P>
In the 200-meter backstroke, Germany's Ralf Braun came in first
in 1:59.74, Croatia's Gordan Kozulj was second in 2:00.07 and
Emanuele Merisi of Italy finished third in 2:00.50
</P>
<P>
European champion and record holder Agnes Kovacs of Hungary
picked up her third gold by successfully defending her title in
the women's 200 breaststroke, winning in 2:27.12. Beatrice Caslaru
of Romania was second in 2:27.80 and Alicja Peczak of Poland third
in 2:28.93.
</P>
<P>
Camelia Potec of Romania won the 200 freestyle in 1:58.79,
followed by Germany's Kerstin Kielgass in 2:00.09 and Natalia
Baranovskaia of Belarus in 2:00.18.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 10-meter platform diving, Ukraine's Elena
Zhupina took the gold with 338.28 points, Spain's Dolores Saez De
Ibara captured the silver and Russia's Svetlana Timoshinina was
third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
