<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Pays Homage to Gen. Torrijos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Panamanians held a ceremony
Saturday to remember the late Gen. Omar Torrijos, who played a
leading role in achieving the withdrawal of the U.S. troops from
Panama and the return of the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 people attended the emotion-laden ceremony held
in the capital in memory of the 18th anniversary of the demise of
Gen. Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
Torrijos, who died in a plane crash in 1981, achieved in 1977
with his diplomatic and political ability the signing of an
agreement, under which the United States must pull out its troops
from Panama and return to Panamanian sovereignty the Panama Canal
by December 31, 1999 to end its more than 80 years of occupation.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Foreign Ministry General Secretary Adolfo
Ahumada praised Torrijos for his efforts to win international
support for the Panamanian struggle to recover its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
December 31 of 1999, when the United States will hand over the
interoceanic waterway to Panamanian sovereignty, will be the first
day of an authentic and real national independence, said former
presidential candidate Martin Torrijos, son of the late general.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
