<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Salvador's Economy to Grow 3.5-4.0 Percent in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The economy of El Salvador
grew by 2.1 percent during the first half of 1999 and the
government plans to achieve a growth between 3.5 percent and 4.0
percent for the whole year, according to report from San Salvador.
</P>
<P>
Economy Minister Miguel Lacayo told the press Saturday that the
new administration, which was sworn in in June, has proposed a
plan to activate the economy, which has gone through a period of
slow growth.
</P>
<P>
Lacayo also said that, next year, the new government will put
emphasis on developing small enterprises, which generate 60
percent of the jobs in El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that exports of Salvadoran products in
the first half of the year amounted to 1.3 billion U.S. dollars,
while imports totaled 2.0 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
