<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Spots Abandoned in Batam, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The tourist spots in Batam,
Indonesia, looked abandoned on Saturday following the clashes
between residents with killing threats reaching the remote
villages in the island.
</P>
<P>
According to the Antara News Agency, the Melur beach, some 40
kilometers from Batam city, where hundreds of local and foreign
tourists used to spend their holidays on Saturdays and Sundays,
had been closed in view of rumors that a certain ethnic group will
be attacked.
</P>
<P>
At the main entrance to Barelang area, where hundreds of cars
and motorcycles used to come, security personnel suggested
visitors to avoid Melur beach in view of the dangerous situation
prevailing there.
</P>
<P>
The streets in Batam city are also abandoned, while well-armed
security personnel in several shopping centers were standing guard
for any possibilities which would harm the interest of the
population, the Antara News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Batamindo industrial estate where people used to see
thousands of busy workers and employees, is also abandoned, while
several public buses looked practically empty.
</P>
<P>
Some 90 foreign investment companies mostly of Singapore,
employing some 160,000 people, are operating in the Batamindo
industrial estate. Most of the workers involved in the clashes
belonged to certain ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, many stores and shopping centers opened their
doors only half-way, while illegally-built houses of members of
the warring groups have mostly been abandoned by their owners
taking refuge elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Batam, just 35 kilometers southeast of Singapore, is a special
industrial zone and also a popular tourist destination for
Singaporeans. Violent clashes between migrant groups from Sumatera
and Flores in Batam since Thursday had claimed at least 13 lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
