<DOCNO> XIE19990801.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French FM Appeals to Enterprises to Return to Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine appealed on Saturday to French enterprises to return to
Algeria, because the security situation has improved in that
country after suffering years of bloody conflict between the
government and Islamic groups.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Parisian newspaper Journal du Dimanche
to be published on Sunday, Vedrine said that most of the French
business leaders whom he has met over the past one year told him
that "the climate has changed (in Algeria) because the army and
police have become efficient" in guaranteeing security.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot but encourage very strongly the French enterprises
to return (to Algeria), at least to support their counterparts who
are already there," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that France and Algeria have reached an agreement
on lessening the control of visa issuing to Algerians applying to
go to France.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine visited Algeria on Thursday and Friday, during which he
held talks with Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika on
normalizing bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
To endorse a new Franco-Algerian strategic partnership, French
President Jacques Chirac plans to make a state visit to Algeria in
September, according to the French daily Le Monde on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
France and Algeria had disputed for years over how to end the
war between the Algerian government and Islamic militants, which
has killed at least 100,000 people since 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
