<HEADLINE> Man Arrested in N.Ireland Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- One man was arrested and a rifle
and a handgun were recovered Saturday night as loyalists and
nationalists clashed again in the Northern Irish town Portadown.
</P>
<P>
There were no reports of any injuries after the man was
arrested following a confrontation in a Catholic area of the town,
said a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
However, Dara O'Hagan of Sinn Fein, the political ally of the
Irish Republican Army (IRA), reported that a shot was fired in the
area and blamed loyalists.
</P>
<P>
"He was tackled by local people and a shot was fired. I think
one man was grazed in the head. People are very frightened and
shocked by what has happened," she said, believing that the man
was a Protestant.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in Portadown, a nationalist man was also arrested after
what police described as "minor disturbances" between Catholics
and Protestants.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Ireland peace process has been placed under review
for the summer period after falling apart over the issue of arms
decommissioning earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein has refused to agree to Ulster Unionist Party demands
for decommissioning before being allowed to sit in a devolved
government for the troubled province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
