<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Morocco's New King Promises Pursuing Policy of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Morocco's new king, Mohammed VI, has
promised to pursue the political reform engaged by his father,
King Hassan II, through adopting political pluralism under a
constitutional monarchy.
</P>
<P>
In his first address to the nation on Friday, King Mohammed VI
said that Morocco needs to solve numerous problems, such as
poverty, social inequality, unemployment, and lack of education
and health care for the poor.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed VI, 36, who inherited the Moroccan throne after his
father died of a heart attack one week ago, said that he will
continue to endorse political pluralism, the rule of law, the
respect of human rights and freedom, while guaranteeing security
and social stability in his country.
</P>
<P>
The young king is known for his admiration for the
constitutional monarchy of Spain under King Juan Carlos, who
introduced democracy to Spain after the death of General Franco in
1975.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would continue to support Socialist Prime
Minister Abderrahmane Youssoufi, who was nominated head of
government by King Hassan last year.
</P>
<P>
Youssoufi, 75, had been King Hassan's opponent for decades and
is regarded as the representative of a political alternative of
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
He has been having difficulties in implementing his power as
prime minister because of resistance to his reform policies from
Morocco's conservative forces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
