<DOCNO> XIE19990801.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRA Ceasefire "Still Holding", Says Sinn Fein </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein Saturday insisted that
the IRA's ceasefire was intact despite the murder this week of a
taxidriver in Belfast and the discovery of a transatlantic arms
smuggling ring in Florida, the United States.
</P>
<P>
The party's chief whip, Alex Maskey, told Reuters that the
IRA's ceasefire was "still holding" despite claims by leading
loyalist David Ervine it was "fraying".
</P>
<P>
Both camps clashed after Ervine, of the Progressive Unionist
Party, which has links to the Ulster Volunteer Force, claimed
loyalists were of the opinion that the IRA's ceasefire was
beginning to "unravel".
</P>
<P>
Ervine said the shooting of the taxidriver Bennett in Belfast
had given rise to suspicions that the IRA was preparing to resume
its paramilitary campaign.
</P>
<P>
However, Maskey responded by accusing Ervine of ignoring
regular loyalist paramilitary violence and recent arms finds in
loyalist areas.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized the demand for Sinn Fein to be expelled from
peace talks, saying that certain people are predictably jumping at
every opportunity on every incident to seek Sinn Fein's exclusion
from the Northern Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"This has been the policy of unionism for some time which has
sought to exclude Sinn Finn and indeed arguably other nationalists
from the peace process. Republicans remain committed to the peace
process," Maskey was quoted by Reuters as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
